SYMPTOM_TEXT: Day of inoculation: [I note that the nurse didn't pull before injecting] Afternoon: heavy drowsiness and tiredness, arm soreness, no redness. Evening: fever (<40C), chills, worst malaise of my life, trembling, weakness, muscle aches all over the body, exhaustion, confusion, sleep disturbance, agitation. Frecuent urination. This lasted until day 3 post inoculation. There were feelings of depression in April in the morning, with oral temperature measurements slightly below 36 C, which I had never seen before (I take my oral temperature regularly: it goes from 36.4-5, to 37.5) even after mild exercise on a rebounder. This lasted a few (at least 3) days, then the morning low temperature disappeared.  On june 1 I wrote to my therapist about my pain on my forearms. I had been trying to hang in there with it, but now it was very frequent, and I used lidocaine cream that day. I was waking up tired and on pain often, with diffuse, mild body aches, and depression. I often felt a need to stretch in the morning, for my muscles (particularly my legs) felt stiff. On july 4 I woke up with strong diffuse body aches. I wanted to rush to the doctor, but realized I couldn't drive in such pain. It was Sunday. After about 1-2 hours the pain mostly subsided. I drove to an Urgent Care. My blood pressure was 144, over what I don't remember. My usual systolic is 120-125. We talked about my PTSD, aches and feelings of depression. He prescribed cyclobenzaprine 5mg, orally, every night. I asked for my blood pressure to be taken again. Now it was 158, over 91, I think (using a manual pump this time). I take the medication that night, the next day I feel much better, and my blood pressure was back to normal. July 25 I am emotionally unstable (from being well to sadness), with chest aches, frequent dissociation (depersonalization and derealization, but never sensory flashbacks), and sudden changes in energy levels, which I blame on having been recently triggered and hormonal changes. I have increasing trouble speaking, which I also blame on anxiety, despite it being far more than usual. At some point I go to health center, where it is dismissed as psychogenic. During august I keep waking up very tired, and now speech difficulties make fluent conversation practically impossible for most of my waking time: I know what I want to say, I understand language, I can read and write, but I cannot get my muscles to respond, or to respond at reasonable speeds. This starts happening to me for a couple of days after getting triggered (which didn't use to be that way) and then the problem kept showing up even when triggers were not involved. I get a sore throat, at take a picture of it. It is just reddened. I go to Health center, and request to be referred to a speech pathologist (the person, sadly, has been unreachable ever since). September: by mid september I am still waking up with stiff muscles, sore legs, feeling tired, and by september 14 (a few days after, I notice, I had several almost non-painful sores in my throat, which then disappeared before the other symptoms showed up) I am woken up numerous times by leg movements that involve dosiflexion of one of my feet at a time (usually my left), extension of the toes, fanning of the toes, and varying degrees of flexion of the knee, sometimes to the point of raising the leg to the height of the abdomen. This may happen 10 times a night. I start to feel scared. I try cyclobenzaprine 5mg for one night. It doesn't make a difference. Almost two weeks in I decide to try to find explanations for the phenomenon. At this point, I am experiencing trembling when I genuflect or kneel at church (a daily activity for years now), I need to use my hand to help myself get up, I still have trouble speaking early in the morning and late at night, and often forget words. I have trouble bringing my laundry basket up the steps i have to: my arms won't respond enough to attempt to raise the basket, even though  I can otherwise move them normally. I end up using my fingers as hooks and going up the steps walking backwards pushing with my legs. I lose the ability to put the recliner of the pew back into place with a flick of my foot as always, even though I can put it down (I don't have a vieo of the event, I think, but I did record a video later of what that motion is supposed to be like). By october 15 I had discovered the human plantar foot reflex, and tested mine following the example of doctors in social media repeatedly. The result was dorsiflexion of the foot, with raising of the big toe, fanning of the other toes, and flexion of the knee on my left leg, no response on my right leg. I have a video about that. It kept holding true on different days, using different objects to elicit the response. I also tried other "equivalent" reflex tests, with same results. I get reffered to a neurologist. Lowering my room temperature helps reduce the frequency of the episodes. I get a referral to a neurologist. About a week later, I accidentally discover something: upon stretching my neck diagonally as far as I can and looking forward again, my teeth chatter. This stops after I push my chin on my chest. It hapens bilaterally, and it is consistently repeatable. I update my doctor about it. I am terrified.  At this point my legs are often feeling sore, particularly my thigh (frontal part). I speak to my parish priest. He gievs me the annointment of the sick. My anxiety got muh better. I start taking a multivitamin for women that doesn't contain iron, looking for a good source of B vitamins. Over the next week, gradually, I had better nights, and symptom improvement, but the Babinski was still there, the leg contractions at night were still there (just not usually wasking me up after my bedroom temperature was moved from 74 to 70F) , an with that my leg trembling has disappeared. My attempt to perform the Romberg test resulted in lack of balance becoming evident. I spoke to a friend doctor, who asked me to stand on one leg. I would stand on my right leg properly, but not on my left (lose balance). OCtober:  I have been having  tender spots all over my body. I take pictures of my touching the sponts that hurt. I also have a mouth sore in my upper lip (picture taken). Sometime I went to urgent care and was told it was probably because I was sleeping so poorly. I was prescribed antidepressants, but I dnd't take them, because I wasn't feelng depressed, and I didn't want meds that carry suicide  thought risk. I also drew and took a picture of the drwaing representing painful areas My neurologist appointment came on nove 17. She reported to not having read my history because she couldn't understand my GPs handwriting. She repeated the Romberg test, my capacity to walk with one foot in foront of the other, both resulted with me losing balance. She looked for something in my eye, but said nothing.  She tested several of my deep tendon reflexes, without any reported findings. She asked me to run my heel pver my shins: that resulted in no respnse on my right leg, but in dorsiflexion of the foot and raising of the big toe and fanning of the toes in my left foot. The same when I asked her to test for a Babinski sign. She ordered a B12 measurement, a thyroid hormone measurement, and a ferriting measurement. My ferritin level was 4.4 (4 something, that's for sure), if I remember correctly, and I was avised to talk to my GP bout iron supplementation or infusions. I started taking 65mg of iron a day since the day after the appointment. All else was great. Since that very night my legs have been awakening me again (particularly my left) with the same moveements as before. I demonstrated the chatter to a psichatric nurse yesterday )I was volunteering for something), and this time the chattering didn't stop through the usual mechanisms. I have a recording of the chatttering the day I went to the neurologist and of yesterday. This time the chattering lasted more than 5 minutes. After it didn't stop the suual way, Ithe nurse recommended that I should record it, and so I did, for more than 5 minutes. The chattering didn't end by the end of the vieo, but it did stop eventually, maybe within 10 minutes of the start. This had never happened befor I also recor mysef eating during the episode, and speaking. The phenomenon doesn't make itdifficult to eat, or swallow, and is not painful. It doesn't feel like the chattering from cold, and can happen at any temperature. I haven't been successful at trying to trigger it while lying down. I can make it stop by tensing some different muscles, but it comes back if I relax my jaw during an episode. I noticed in the video that, even whenI stop it like this, my face doesn't look quite right. I also noticed that I blinked a lot, but I don't remember if the wind was causing that. It did make it difficul for me to speak at some point, which is evidenced in the video. The mechanisms that I used and work for me when I am having difficulty speaking due to anxiety had absolutely no effect in this case. I may note that the leg movements aren't only present while I sleep, but also when I am close to falling asleep. Also, that sometimes (occassionally) they involve a rather circular motion of the foot, resulting in the foot "climbimg" up the bed, flesing upwards, thento the left, then downard as if rgoing back to the neutral position, releatedly and wuickly in a successive motion about three times or two.. Also that the contractions last a few seconds. I don't feel that I have any control over the foot during those moments. Another note, which I don't know how relevant it may be, is that I shiver very strongly:my whole back sways, my butt moves widely, my head goes out of position, and I have never seen anyone shiver like that. It hasn't always been this way, but I don't remember how long this has been. My doctor, listed here, I think, was not at the Health center when I had the severe and almost constant difficulty speaking. My academic advisor has seen it. A lot of the content of this long text has been based, not only on memory, but on writings that I directed to my therapist or friends reporting to her what was going on soon after the events took place, so when dates are stated or numbers are given they are accurate unless doubt is expressed, to  the best of my ability. FIRST DOSE: Woke up following morning with sudden hearing loss. Left ear nearly no hearing at all present, Right ear only able to hear some sounds. Both ears unable to hear running water such as a faucet turned on and washing hands, unable to hear sausage sizzling in a hot pan when standing directly in front of hot pan, unable to hear swishing sounds of items being rubbed together or people walking near by. Unable to hear the sounds similar to the sound the letters "s" and "f" make.  VERY LOUD ringing in ears both left and right, Left more frequently.  Changes in hearing was never an issue prior to vaccination. It comes and goes and lasts all day/ night sometimes for multiple days at a time before it settles down. Once settled it comes back on very suddenly without warning or trigger. Almost as if its being turned on and off again by a switch or button. This causes great frustration, anxiety and uncertainty of surroundings due to sudden lack of hearing.   SECOND DOSE: Upon getting the 2nd dose no reactions until approximately 14 hours afterward. Expecting to feel flu-like symptoms and expecting the need to rest at the first signs of feeling not well, I laid back down to rest about an hour after waking up from a full night of rest. This was day 1 and included much of expected flu-like symptoms: chills, hot spells, desire to sleep, able to keep fluids in but not interested in eating food.  Day 2: Included all of symptoms from day 1 but more severe. Also included uncontrollable muscular spasms almost like convulsing. Unable to walk upright but able to crawl on all four to get to the bathroom and back to bed. Crying in severe pain and unable to get any rest due to the uncontrollable body movements. By about 4pm of dealing with excruciating pains, chills, sweats, migraine feeling headache. Unable to eat but able to keep in very small sips of Gatorade. Took an adult dose of NyQuil Severe, able to rest eyes for about an hour even while arms and leg muscles continuing to convulse involuntarily. Declined going to hospital and declined ambulance call.  Day 3: Exactly like day 2 but able to control symptoms more with additional NyQuil Severe dosages taken every 4hrs even though the symptoms would break through at about 2.5hrs. Again declined EMS and hospital visit. Felt well enough to try walking to the bathroom, woke up after an undetermined amount of time on closet floor with face and hair covered in blood and dried to the floor. Unaware of loosing consciousness or hitting face/ head on floor or loss of bladder. Once alert, able to move back to bed by crawling very slowly and requesting for spouse to assist in cleaning up mess on face and floor. Very concerned spouse advised to call EMS or hospital, but it was again declined as to not add additional expenses to the family budget and or create any other was to possibly get exposed to contracting COVID-19. Also was believed the patient would just be sent back home to rest without any real treatment completed. It was believed to be a waste of time and recourses in addition to a waste of time and money and not worth the added risks.  Day 4: Some improvements but all symptoms the same just not as severe as prior two days.  This severe unwell feeling continued for two weeks and the involuntary muscular spams began to slow down but not stop until day 6.  Day 7: able to go about normal routine although very weak and needing to take many breaks to rest and drink some fluids. No solid foods other than chicken broth and Jello at this point. This continued until Day 13.  Went to see doctor on day 8 of 2nd vaccine and discussed everything with her. She was very worried that I had such a severe adverse reaction and disappointed to not receive assistance through EMS or ER. She requested that this form be filled out and that my symptoms be reported. I didn't really want to as it was already bad enough to try and catch up on my daily life but to recount everything I went through in that time is daunting. Not to mention that I am still having severe ear issues with sudden loss of hearing and LOUD tinnitus. It comes and goes like someone turning it on and off. I have no history of hearing issues, random tinnitus or hearing loss. This is completely new since becoming vaccinated with the Covid Vaccine. I am concerned this is a long term effect as now it has been three months with no improvements. It seems like it may be increasing in frequency and the amount of hearing loss is more and lasting longer than before. Its beyond frustrating!  Now I am in a position where it is recommended that I do not get a booster vaccine and to wait on vaccinating our young children for they could have a similar or worse reaction to the vaccine. We are at a complete loss of what is the best action to protect our children!! We've been mostly isolated for nearly two years and our kids have been homeschooled during this time. They aren't playing sports or seeing any friends and family in person. This is a very unfair situation with no good answers!!!
LAB_DATA: Full blood labs checked at last doctor visit. August 2021
CUR_ILL: NONE, just hearing issues immediately following first vaccine but seemed to be back to normal at the time of 2 vaccine dose.

My first Pfizer vaccine was on May 15, 2021 and did not experience any reaction. The second Pfizer Vaccine was on June 5th, 2021. On June 18th, 2021 I started to feel pain and tingling in my left arm and left two fingers, as well as my face. I went to the emergency room and had a CT scan, EKG and blood test and everything came back normal. On June 21, 2021 I saw a Neurologist. I had an MRI done which found two very small incidental findings, one on my Left Thalamus and on my Pituitary. On June 25, 2021, I started to feel tingling in both legs from my knees down. On July 16, 2021 I started to get a really bad migraine and my face started to feel warm and my head felt hazy. This lasted until July 21, 2021. Since my symptoms started, I saw 3 Neurologists, Pituitary specialist and a Hematologist and none thought my symptoms were coming from the 2 findings and all other tests were normal. Things have gotten better but on occasion I feel tingling and muscle twitches in my legs.

But that night I woke up with a burning fever (102.2), my whole body was aching to the point where even the pores in my skin were hurting; despite the high fever, I felt terribly cold and shivery. I took one Tylenol and tried to go back to bed. By 10-11 am the next morning, my temperature had gone down to 101 but I still felt incredibly weak and cold, could barely mange to lift the frying pan or pour water out of the jug. I took another Tylenol around noon on November 20 with food. Couldn't taste the food either so it was hard to eat. Took more Tylenol at 6-8 hour intervals and by Sunday afternoon (today), my temperature returned to normal. Still feeling horribly weak and achey.

I received my second dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Nov. 3. On Nov. 12, I had a kale salad for dinner and thought it tasted strange, like rubber. At the time I thought it was just the taste of kale, because I'd never had raw kale before. But since then, I've noticed the same very weird burnt rubber taste and smell (both) whenever I have coffee, white wine, kale, turkey, and a few other foods ? those are just the ones I am most certain about because I drink coffee every day and have wine a few times a week. I have never tasted or smelled this particular taste/smell before and am concerned that it is parosmia from the vaccine. It has not gone away yet as of today 11-21-21. I have not yet sought any treatment. I am hoping my regular sense of taste and smell will return. I did not lose my taste or smell, and I can still taste and smell everything. It?s just that some foods now have that weird burnt rubber taste and smell, but they never used to.   I should also note that I was diagnosed with Covid 19 on Dec 30, 2020. I was sick for about two weeks and I did lose my taste and smell completely for about 10 days. Then my taste and smell came back. Also I did not experience any distortion of taste or smell. I did, however, feel very exhausted and I had acid reflux throat issues for the next two months. I did see an ENT, who agreed that my symptoms could be long Covid. Those throat issues finally cleared up at the end of May 2021.  Now I am really confused as to why I would experience parosmia (taste and smell distortion) about 9 days after my second dose of Pfizer, but never before when I actually had Covid.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was in his usual state of health until 48 hours after receiving his 3rd "booster" Moderna COVID vaccine. He presented in cardiogenic shock as evidenced by hypotension, elevated lactate, CT imaging showing reversal/reflux of contrast in the IVC and hepatic veins, and echo showing severe LV dysfunction (EF 10%) with a prior echo that was EF 50% in 2020.   The patient suffered refractory hypotension despite efforts to maintain blood pressures with multiple pressors and eventually developed PEA arrest.  Troponin minimally positive on admission and rose to a high level, suggesting a possible etiology of myocardial infarction (likely LAD territory based on echo) versus myocarditis as a result of the vaccine booster.  The patient unfortunately was pronounced deceased on 11/21/21 about 8 hours after presentation to the ED.
HISTORY: Complete Heart Block s/p Permanent Pacemaker, atrial fibrillation, diabetes, hypertension

After I gave the patient her flu shot, I reached for the Moderna dose, believing it was Pfizer neglecting to check the volume and label on the syringe. I immediately realized my mistake and notified the patient when I prepared to vaccinate the husband, only to see the Moderna dose was missing. The patient was upset and insistent on receiving Pfizer. She grew concerned of an allergic reaction to Moderna. I deeply apologized and assured her CDC has approved Pfizer and Moderna to be mixed, and due to her history of Pfizer doses with no reactions, it is unlikely she would react with Moderna. My assistant called my supervisor over, and she repeated to the patient CDC's approval as well as addressing the patient's safety concerns. We monitored the patient for over 15 minutes observing no reaction.

Approximately 14 days after the  1st does of the Covid vaccine was administered, I noticed a rash at the injection site (upper left arm).  This rash was red, slightly bumpy, and itchy.  Over the next 10 days the rash spread down my left arm across my chest, and down my right arm.  The rash was hot to the touch and was itchy.  I received by 2nd dose of the Covid vaccine on 2/24/21.  The itching became quite severe and it kept me awake at night.   Over the counter itch treatments did not help alleviate the rash or the itching.  On 3/3/2021, I finally went to an urgent care facility to get help to stop the itching.  I was given a steroid injection, a topical hydrocortisone prescription, and told to take Claritin/Zyrtec Daily.   I had temporary relief of the rash and itching for about a week to 10 days  but the rash and itch returned on my arms and chest and spread up my neck, on my ears, and across my back.  I returned to the urgent care facility on 3/18/21 .  They prescribed a 7 day oral steroid treatment and told me to continue to take the Zyrtec and treat with over the counter itch ointment.  I followed up these urgent care visits with a visit to my primary care physician on 3/26/21.  The rash was still present at this appointment but the rash and itch had started to improve.  Blood work taken at the appointment showed Eosinophils sl high (possible allergies).  The rash and the itch finally resolved by around 4/3/2021.

Patient discharged after a 4-day inpatient stay 11/13-11/17/21 The patient is a 74 y.o. Female who presents with HA, cough, wheezing, body aches, nausea, diarrhea, and poor PO intake. She states her symptoms started on 11/10/21. She currently lives with her daughter and son-in-law, both of whom are COVID+. She states as soon as she started to get sick, she knew it was COVID. She states she has not been able to eat or normally drink for the last few days as her symptoms progressed due to nausea.   On arrival to ED, she was tachypneic and hypoxic to 89% on room air. COVID test was positive. CMP showed mild hyperkalemia, BUN 28, Cr 1.3, Alk Phos 143. CBC showed mild leukocytosis at 11.49 with lymphopenia on the differential. Troponin x1 was 14 (indeterminate). Her lactic acid and BNP were normal. EKG showed paced rhythm, no ST elevation or depression. D-dimer was elevated at 1070. CTA thorax showed no evidence of PE but limited study, no additional signs of cardiopulmonary disease. She was given 500ml IV NS and subsequently admitted to the hospital for acute hypoxic respiratory failure due to Acute COPD exacerbation caused by COVID-19 infection.   Upon arrival to the floor, the patient's blood pressure was still soft, and she was given another 500ml IV NS, to which she responded well. She was started on a 5-day course of remdesivir, a 10-day course of steroids, and a 3-day course of Azithromycin with regular duo-neb treatments. Due to her dehydration and hypotension on admission, we held her Entresto, sotalol, and spironolactone; they remained on hold until discharge for blood pressures in the 110's/70's. She showed steady improvement in wheeze and oxygen requirements, reaching mid 90's saturation on room air by day 3. She completed remdesivir course and was medically and vitally stable for discharge home with a 5-day course of oral steroids.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: COVID Breakthrough case

Briefly, patient presents with vomiting that 10 episodes of nonbloody nonbilious per day since receiving his first Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine 48 hours ago. No fevers, diarrhea, apparent headache.     Exam (after Zofran) showed: Gen: Nontoxic appearing, no acute distress, alert and active, playing with phone; HEENT: mucus membranes dry, PERRL, EOMI, normal conjunctiva, neck supple without LAN; Card: RRR, no murmur, good perfusion; Lungs: CTAB, good air entry, no increased WOB; Abd: soft, non-tender, non-distended, no masses; Ext: warm and well perfused, moving all extremities; Skin: no rashes; GU: Testes do not appear to swollen, tender to palpation, and have normal cremasteric reflex bilaterally     Symptoms likely due to post vaccine reaction versus viral illness with component of gastroenteritis. Less likely appendicitis or other concerning intraabdominal pathology given benign abdominal exam. Do not suspect increased ICP given normal neuro exam and lack of apparent HA.  GU exam is reassuring against hernia or torsion as etiology.  Given age, UTI is less likely but discussed with family and obtained urinalysis which was reassuring against UTI, ketones likely due to dehydration.  Covid swab and rapid strep sent, strep negative, COVID pending.  Given Zofran and PO challenged tolerated multiple glasses of water without vomiting. Patient safe for discharge to home with supportive care and PCP follow up, prescribed short course of zofran in case of ongoing vomiting. Family in agreement with plan and verbalize understanding of signs and symptoms to return to care. Final Diagnosis  1. Vomiting R11.10 2. Dehydration E86.0 3. Autism spectrum disorder F84.9
LAB_DATA: UA negative except for large ketones (160) Throat culture, Group A strep - negative SARS CoV-s PCR, Resp, Qual - negative

Chief complaint - COVID-19 HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: Patient is a 75 y.o. female with history of cardiomyopathy, hypertension, IBS, fibromyalgia, GERD, osteoarthritis, CVA and PMR who presents today with gradual weakness over the last 6 months, acutely worse in the last week with 2 days of upper respiratory symptoms.  Patient states that since being diagnosed with PMR and June of 2021 she has had steadily increasing weakness and no significant improvement in her pain since starting the prednisone.  She has been engaged in a long and slow taper over this time.  Over the last week patient had increasing pain in her back and generalized muscle aches alongside increasing fatigue and weakness.  Two days ago she started to develop upper respiratory symptoms with rhinorrhea, congestion, dry cough and fever.  Patient has chronic nausea that is unchanged along with alternating diarrhea and constipation that is also unchanged.  On the day of admission patient was feeling weak, she stated that she was sitting in her chair watching television and when she went to stand up she had an episode of incontinence which was unusual for her.  She got herself cleaned up and then when she sat back down had another episode of incontinence.  Patient was feeling off and she contacted her daughter as well as the "gentleman who lives upstairs" and they advised that she go to the emergency department to get evaluated.  Patient initially declined but was having worsening pain in her back muscles and was feeling febrile  and weak so in for evaluation. Emergency department course:  On presentation to the emergency department patient was febrile at 38.9� C, pulse 101, respiratory rate 28 and blood pressure 159/89.  Heart rate remained elevated between 101 and 110. Laboratory workup performed, CMP unremarkable, magnesium 1.9, phosphorus 3.1, troponin was not elevated at 12, procalcitonin 0.06.  Urinalysis was negative for infection with only trace leukocyte esterase.  COVID-19 PCR was positive.  Venous blood gas showed pH of 7.4 and pCO2 of 41.7.  Patient's lactic acid is mildly elevated 2.1.  Complete blood count showed hemoglobin 11.4 and WBC count of 8.38.  Chest x-ray showed no evidence of pneumonia.  Peripheral blood cultures were obtained and patient was given a 1 L saline bolus and 1 g of Tylenol.  Patient was noted to be weak and required assistance from nursing to get up to the bedside commode.  Patient's husband did not feel that she was safe to return home with her weakness.  Patient will be admitted for observation, PT and OT. ASSESSMENT / PLAN: COVID-19 pneumonia Generalized weakness Patient has had 2-3 days of upper respiratory symptoms and worsening weakness.  She has had generalized weakness steadily worsening over the past 6 months. Patient is not hypoxic and symptoms have been present for less than 10 days, she does not qualify for remdesivir or Decadron. Main Reason for admission is weakness, patient and a live-in companion did not feel comfortable with discharge home due to level of assistance needed. There was initial concern for stroke.  CT head was negative for acute abnormalities.  CT angiogram head and neck did show tubular 3 mm aneurysm protruding from the carotid arteries.  Other notable tests were positive COVID PCR, positive UA, hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia, elevated D-dimer and inflammatory markers.  Chest x-ray was clear.  Blood cultures were obtained which remained negative.  Patient was started on Rocephin. Patient was admitted for further assessment and management.  Neurology were on consult.  MRI of the brain did not show evidence of acute ischemic infarction, although there was comment on mild chronic small-vessel ischemic changes, chronic bilateral basal ganglia lacunar infarctions, age-appropriate brain atrophy.  Neurology recommended aspirin and statin as well as optimizing cardiovascular risk profile, they also recommended zio patch on discharge and outpatient neurosurgery follow-up for small aneurysms.  Patient's confusion improved by the following day.  Based on her history, she did qualify for monoclonal antibody for COVID and received this on 11/17.  Patient's respiratory status was monitored closely and did not require oxygen.  Initially physical therapy recommended subacute rehabilitation, however this changed to home with PT/OT/RN services after she recovered from her infectious symptoms.  She was discharged home with home care on 11/19/2021.

After receiving the first dose of Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine, I started feeling fatigue especially noticeable when running or exercises elevating heart rate. I tried to run in the evening I received the first dose and felt fatigue but pushed myself.  For the next three weeks I felt tired and not like myself when trying to exercise. My resting heart rate, which i monitored regularly with a fitness tracker and usually about 55 bpm, did not drop below 80 bpm for about three days after the vaccine. When performing exercises which raise heart rate Iwas feeling unusual fatigue, shortness of breath, and dull ache at the heart area.  Sometimes while sitting  I would get a jabbing feeling and would sigh more often Three weeks later, at about the time i needed to get the second dose, my feelings did not improve so I visited my family care doctor, who ran some blood work to rule out any deficiencies and then referred me to a cardiologist. At this point I stopped any exercising. My cardio testing was done at about 6 weeks after the initial vaccine and thankfully showed my heart was ok. I actually started to feel better about the 5th week. Maybe stopping the cardio heart exercises for a while helped me recover. A video i came across from a doctor suggested that cardio and strenuous exercises should be avoided for at least a week after the vaccine is administered to reduce the chance of heart issues. I wish I had known that before as i would have stopped training. They should do more to make that information known so others don't experience these symptoms or worse because  sometimes the damage may be irreversible.
LAB_DATA: blood panel work including iron, vitamin d, and thyroid, C-reactive protein, Stress w/ echo cardio test

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient discharged after (2) day inpatient stay 11/12-11/14/2021 Patient is a 62 y.o. female with past medical history significant for essential hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, non-insulin dependent and hyperlipidemia who presented to the ED with right sided chest pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and dry cough. In the ED, she was hemodynamically stable, afebrile and non-hypoxic on room air. Covid 19 PCR was positive. CXR obtained and negative for acute cardiopulmonary process. Lab work revealed hyponatremia with Na 121. Troponin x2 was 7 -> 8 and EKG without acute ischemic changes. While in the ED, the patient received 1L IV fluid with improvement in sodium level to 126. She was admitted for further management.   Hyponatremia felt likely hypovolemic secondary to vomiting and diarrhea in setting of Covid 19 infection. Home hctz was held and she was given gentle IV fluids. Her sodium levels slowly improved over the next 48 hours. She was without dyspnea, had no further chest pain and remained on room air. She felt much improved and felt stable for discharge. She was instructed to stay hydrated, continue to hold hctz and follow up with her PCP within one week for repeat lab work and follow up. She was discharged home with her husband in stable condition.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mouth got an odd taste-dry- change in sensation which persists. Feeling that the end of the tongue is burnt but without pain or change in taste. Sensation is noticeable when doing little (like driving) but is forgotten about when busy.   Approximately 10-12 weeks after vaccination I started waking up in the night with tingling in the left arm (where injection was). This continued for several weeks and got worse- till pain was occurring in the left back arm (ulnar nerve pain). It progress to neck pain.  There is pain at the shoulder back neck to the armpit where the nerves go down the arm.
LAB_DATA: Tried heart burn medicine, yeast swab (neg), blood chemistry check (all normal), nasal scope. Diagnosis is suspected burning mouth syndrome. Examination of the tongue shows raised bumps indicating inflammation.  For Ulnar nerve pain, I first was given dry needling with lidocane (3x over 6 weeks) and 7 week of PT without resolution of symptoms, an MRI and EMG was performed. MRI shows no cervical radiculopathy, EMG shows slow nerve firing, no suggestion of cervical radiculopathy- and the indication is that it is from the elbow. Muscle Relaxers and advil (2x daily) are advised. No event has been identified for trauma to the elbow.

Negative for chest tightness, shortness of breath and wheezing.    Patient's initial nausea/vomiting was secondary to Covid-19; she also had AKI and dehydration secondary to that. She was treated supportively with IVF, electrolyte replacement, antiemetics and she improved. Her hyponatremia improved too with improvement of her fluid status. She didn't have any other covid symptoms; didn't have any respiratory problems and didn't require oxygen. She was treated with ceftriaxone for UTI; after her symptoms persisted repeat UA was done which still showed elevated WBCs so she was given a dose of fosfomycin which relieved her symptoms. She didn't have any growth in her cultures/ During hospital stay, she had increased ostomy output and had AKI and electrolyte depletion secondary to that which resolved with supportive care. She has been tried multiple therapies for high output stoma in past unsuccessfully; she was open to trying soluble fibers so polycarbophil was started. She takes 500 ml NS and  2 gm MG IV through her port every other day and gets weekly labs that is sent over to her gastroenterologist's office who adjusts her fluid and electrolytes; this was continued at discharge. PT/OT recommended acute rehab so patient stayed waiting on that but her insurance denied it so patient opted to go home with home health, PT, OT; which was arranged for her at discharge.. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Got the vaccine around 1600 on Thursday, November 18th. Woke up in the middle of the night with my arm on fire and painful. On Friday, around 1200 I started getting chills. My temp was normal, but I couldn't get warm or stay warm. I was fatigued and nauseous. I took ibuprofen (~500mg) around 1400. I started feeling better around 1800 that night. I had a hard time sleeping as my arm was still hurting and it was hot, swollen and sensitive to the touch at the injection site. On Sunday, I noticed the my arm was still swollen, sensitive to touch, itchy and hot. When I looked I noticed I had 2 red rashes (one about the size of a quarter, the other about 2" long and about 1" wide). I took pictures and had made marks to identify if it spreads. On Monday, 22 November, the rash has spread outside of the marks from the previous day. My arm is still swollen, itchy, hot and hurts to touch and move sometimes.

She has gradually worsened to the point in which she had rigors overnight and was too weak to get out of bed today.  She has a very mild cough but notes dyspnea.  She notes nausea without vomiting. She had diarrhea at baseline which has not changed. Today she had one episode of bright red hemoptysis while coughing.  She is recovering from right rib fractures in which she describes a burning nerve pain to her right ribs.  The patient also endorses dysuria.  The patient had COVID-19 in January, 2021.  She received mono-clonal antibodies and did not require hospitalization.  She was then vaccinated x 2 with the Pfizer vaccine (last dose 5/2021).  On chart review, the patient was on Budesonide at the time of the vaccine. In the ER, the patient had T 37.2 C, hypoxia with SpO2 of 86%, RR 26.  Other vital signs were normal.  CXR overall low inspiratory volumes with areas of confluent bilateral mid and lower lung predominant airspace opacities suggesting Covid pneumonitis.  Labs significant for creatinine 1.11, magnesium 1.3, alk-phos 234, AST 70 ALT 86, WBC 14.84.  The patient was given 1 g of Tylenol, 6 mg of Decadron, 2 g of magnesium sulfate. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient returned for his second dose of the Covid-19 Moderna vaccine on 11/19/21. Patient stated that he waited so long to get his second dose because he had a bad reaction to his first dose.   Patient stated that immediately following his first dose of the vaccine he felt his heart racing, dizziness, and weakness. Patient stated that he also developed nausea, left sided chest pain. These symptoms were stated to last about a week. During that  time the patient rested in bed but was unable to see his doctor.   Most of his symptoms resolved after about 1 week, but the patient reports that he still had lingering  "brain fog", dizziness, and weakness. These symptoms lingered for about a month. The patient reports that he attempted to contact his primary doctor about the incident and whether he should return for a second dose, but was never able to actually get an appointment.   When the patient came in for his second dose on 11/19/21 he reported that all symptoms had resolved.  After questioning about his reaction to the first dose, we did not give the patient his second dose of Moderna due to concerns of potential myocarditis, pericarditis and/or allergy following his first shot of Moderna. The patient declined receiving the Janssen vaccine. Patient was instructed to follow up with his primary care physician and a cardiologist.
ALLERGIES: Patient reported a severe allergy with hives to Ritalin

Normal/expected side effects occurred during the first 24-36 hours after receiving my COVID-19 booster shot. I opted to get the Pfizer booster because I'd had a previous adverse reaction to the second dose of the Moderna vaccine, and I'd hoped to avoid the same reaction this time.  In the same manner as my previous adverse reaction, the expected side effects went away and then I began to experience nerve pain and tingling, primarily in legs and feet, 5 days after (on 11/15/21) receiving my booster. I was able to sleep through the pain this time. I also took Amitriptyline on 11/15/21 and 11/16/21 in an effort to help me sleep and better manage the nerve pain. By 11/17/21, the nerve pain and tingling seemed to be improving in my lower extremities and it progressed more into my chest, abdomen, and upper extremities. I also experienced constipation and difficulty urinating during this time. This all made it difficult to eat or drink fluids. I didn't experience relief from constipation until 11/19/21 (after two doses of magnesium citrate and senna/colace) and wasn't able to eat a full meal until 11/21/21.  At this time, some slight tingling and chest pain still exist, more so on the left side of my body. I did not seek any medical attention this time given the fact that I went to urgent care and the ER during my previous reaction, and nothing really helped except for time.
OTHER_MEDS: Truvada, Lisinopril-HCTZ, Metoprolol, adult multivitamin, vitamin D supplement, vitamin B12 supplement

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the vaccine, a few days later I had started to feel a tingling and numbness on the right side of my face. It starts with my right eye down to the middle of my chin all the way though my cheek, lip, and then my tongue. Initially it felt like there was a hair or feather touching my skin, nut nothing was ever there. Over time it got more and more numb. It felt like nothing in that area. It didn't affect my muscles because i could still move my cheek, neck, and jaw. When I would shave in the morning it would feel like I was scrapping my right cheek and it was painful. It eventually subsided as a numb feeling in my lip and the right side of my tongue.  Prior to receiving the vaccine, I wasn't sick or had any illnesses. I went to the dentist to see if I had a tooth in my mouth that was causing these feelings, but the x-rays showed nothing. Then I went to a neurologist and did more test. I haven't received a diagnosis for my condition yet.  None of the doctors can prove that it was because of the COVID-19 vaccine.
LAB_DATA: X-ray- showed nothing (4/8/2021) Blood work- slight positive ANA (10/6/2021) MRI- showed no abnormality (10/19/2021)
